      Lately, I've been working on a bevy of locally-focused projects including two public design exhibitions. In May, my show <strong><a href="https://www.ronbronson.design/posts/parliament-of-neighbors">"A Parliament of Neighbors"</a></strong> debuted at an experimental art gallery hosted at a Portland mall. Last fall, I organized a public design exhibit called <strong><a href"https://www.ronbronson.design/posts/designers-share">The Designer's Share of the Problem"</a> </strong>for the Portland Design Festival. </p>

<p>In my day job, I'm Head of Design at 18F. I lead a talented team of 35 designers and design managers in tackling large-scale digital transformation projects and shaping greenfield initiatives. Together with product, engineering, and government acquisition professionals, we leverage iterative and Agile practices to build and procure technology solutions for the federal government. 
       </p>

<p>For the past few years, I've been thinking aloud about the ways designers working in tech contribute to the larger problems, and argue that we need more than "ethics codes" to govern our work, but rather, a cadre of professionals -- not just designers -- who work in the public interest. I've given talks about Consequence Design around the world over the past few years. </p>

